SIMPLE: toy
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Toy
<hw>Toy</hw> <pr>(toi)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>tuid</ets>
tools, implements, stuff, trash, speel<ets>tuig</ets> playthings, toys;
akin to G. <ets>zeug</ets> stuff, materials, MNG. <ets>ziuc</ets>, Icel.
<ets>tygi</ets> gear; all ultimately from the root of E. <ets>tug</ets>,
v. t.; cf. G. <ets>zeugen</ets> to beget, MHG. <ets>ziugen</ets> to
beget, make ready, procure. See <er>Tug</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A plaything for children; a bawble.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thing for amusement, but of no real value; an
article of trade of little value; a trifle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They exchange for knives, glasses, and such <qex>toys</qex>, great
abundance of gold and pearl.</q> <rj><qau>Abr. Abbot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A wild fancy; an odd conceit; idle sport; folly;
trifling opinion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To fly about playing their wanton <qex>toys</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What if a <qex>toy</qex> take 'em in the heels now, and they all
run away.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor light and idle <qex>toys</qex> my lines may vainly swell.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Amorous dalliance; play; sport; pastime.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To dally thus with death is no fit <qex>toy</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An old story; a silly tale.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <ety>[Probably the same word.]</ety> <def>A headdress of
linen or woolen, that hangs down over the shoulders, worn by old women
of the lower classes; -- called also <altname>toy mutch</altname>.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Having, moreover, put on her clean
<xex>toy</xex>, rokelay, and scarlet plaid.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Toy
<hw>Toy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>toyed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>toying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To dally amorously; to trifle; to
play.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>toy</qex>, to wanton, dally, smile and jest.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Toy
<hw>Toy</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To treat foolishly.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>E. Dering (1576).</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toyear</ent>⟦br⟧
